04618nam a22007095i 9781400833740DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20112009nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1002222345  a97814008337407 a10.1515/97814008337402doi  a(DE-B1597)453695  a(OCoLC)979592900  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a338.9173223  aMK 21002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123031:1 aEkbladh, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Great American Mission :bModernization and the Construction of an American World Order /cDavid Ekbladh.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2011] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b17 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerica in the World ;v600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. THE RISE OF AN AMERICAN STYLE OF DEVELOPMENT, 1914–1937 -- t2. THE ONLY ROAD FOR MANKIND -- t3. A GOSPEL OF LIBERALISM -- t4. “THE PROVING GROUND” -- t5. “THE GREAT AMERICAN MISSION” -- t6. A TVA ON THE MEKONG -- t7. “EVERYTHING IS GOING WRONG” -- t8. NEW DEVELOPMENTS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Great American Mission traces how America's global modernization efforts during the twentieth century were a means to remake the world in its own image. David Ekbladh shows that the emerging concept of modernization combined existing development ideas from the Depression. He describes how ambitious New Deal programs like the Tennessee Valley Authority became symbols of American liberalism's ability to marshal the social sciences, state planning, civil society, and technology to produce extensive social and economic change. For proponents, it became a valuable weapon to check the influence of menacing ideologies such as Fascism and Communism. Modernization took on profound geopolitical importance as the United States grappled with these threats. After World War II, modernization remained a means to contain the growing influence of the Soviet Union. Ekbladh demonstrates how U.S.-led nation-building efforts in global hot spots, enlisting an array of nongovernmental groups and international organizations, were a basic part of American strategy in the Cold War. However, a close connection to the Vietnam War and the upheavals of the 1960s would discredit modernization. The end of the Cold War further obscured modernization's mission, but many of its assumptions regained prominence after September 11 as the United States moved to contain new threats. Using new sources and perspectives, The Great American Mission offers new and challenging interpretations of America's ideological motivations and humanitarian responsibilities abroad.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aEconomic assistance, AmericanxHistory. 0aEconomic developmentzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aIndustrial policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140083374040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400833740423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400833740.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK